\subsubsection{Soil moisture content}\label{sub:smc}
Both models were initialised with the same soil moisture content. It was found that for all sites the soil moisture content in JULES was generally lower than in CTESSEL for al soil layers. The precipitation is the same in both cases and both models use \citet{VanGenuchten1980} hydraulic scheme with equal parameters where possible (Table \ref{tab:soil_VG}). However despite these efforts there are inherent differences in the computation of the soil water fluxes. As an example, the volumetric soil moisture content for each soil layer at two of the simulated sites is shown in Figure \ref{fig:sm}. Each panel corresponds to each of the soil layers. The different time scale of variations in soil moisture content can be appreciated at each layer. The soil moisture content in the top layer is varies more quickly following the precipitation signal. As depth increases, the soil moisture content variability decreases. 
The soil moisture content used as initialisation state was chosen to be in equilibrium for JULES, it can be seen in the 4th panel how both models are started with the same soil moisture, however CTESSEL's soil moisture increases towards a higher equilibrium. Despite the possible discrepancies in the hydraulic scheme and equilibrium state, larger evaporation seen in JULES also plays a role in the drier layers found for JULES for all soil layers. Soil evaporation affects exclusively the first layer whereas vegetation's transpiration has the potential to deplete moisture from all layers trough root extraction. The lower water content has implications as it restricts GPP quite strongly. The JULES soil moisture factor for these two and all other sites is shown in Figure \ref{fig:beta}.
% 
\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \subfloat[]{
    \includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/soilmoisture/sm_m3_m3_BEBra.png}
    \label{fig:sm_BEBra}}
%\subfloat[]{
%\includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/soilmoisture/sm_m3_m3_ITRo1.png}
%\label{fig:sm_ITRo1}}
    \subfloat[]{
    \includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/soilmoisture/sm_m3_m3_NLCa1.png}
    \label{fig:sm_NLCa1}}
    \caption{Volumetric soil moisture at each soil layer as reproduced by both models for two sites: BE-Bra at a forest site \protect\subref{fig:sm_BEBra} and NL-Ca1 at a grass site \protect\subref{fig:sm_NLCa1}. For JULES, it can be noted how for BE-Bra the deepest layer has a strong role in determining the soil moisture stress on photosynthesis, as seen by the low soil moisture content in years 2006 and 2007 matching the low values of \protect$\beta$ in Figure \protect\ref{fig:BEBra_beta}; whereas in NL-Ca1, the uppermost layer determines the soil moisture stress, as seen by the low  soil moisture content in years 2003, 2004 and 2006 matching the low values of \protect$\beta$ in Figure \protect\ref{fig:NLCa1_beta}.}
\label{fig:sm}
\end{figure}
