\caption{Soil moisture stress factor ($\beta$) for each JULES simulation.}
\label{fig:beta}
\end{figure}
\clearpage
\subsubsection{Seasonal means and ecosystem water use efficiency}
%year averages
The monthly means of GPP and LE of all modelled years have been averaged together for a better illustration of the seasonal variation at each site (first two columns in Figure \ref{fig:avg}). In the third column, the relation between latent heat and carbon assimilation is presented. It has been denominated as water use efficiency and has been calculated simply as:
\begin{equation}
WUE = \frac{GPP}{LE} 
\end{equation}
It must be noted that the latent heat in the denominator includes evaporative flux from soil and direct evaporation from the canopy interception as well as stomatal transpiration,  while other definitions of WUE relate the GPP to only the transpired water. This extended calculation can be compared against observations, as the GPP/LE ratio can be derived from the measured fluxes. The units of WUE calculated in this manner are $\mu$mol of carbon per unit of evaporative energy. In winter due to the small magnitude of both fluxes, the WUE values are more variable and should not be considered,  in Figure \ref{fig:CZBK1_avg} some values of CTESSEL were removed.\\
%
\begin{figure}
      	\centering
 	\subfloat[FR-Hes]{\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/seasonal/FRHesGPP_LE_WUE_seasonal.png}
        \label{fig:FRHes_avg}}
	\subfloat[BE-Vie]{\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/seasonal/BEVieGPP_LE_WUE_seasonal.png}
        \label{fig:BEVie_avg}}
        \subfloat[BE-Bra]{\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/seasonal/BEBraGPP_LE_WUE_seasonal.png}
        \label{fig:BEBra_avg}}
 	\subfloat[NL-Loo]{\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/seasonal/NLLooGPP_LE_WUE_seasonal.png}
        \label{fig:NLLoo_avg}}
        \caption{Seasonal average}
\end{figure}
\begin{figure}
        \centering
        \ContinuedFloat
 	\subfloat[DE-Tha]{\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/seasonal/DEThaGPP_LE_WUE_seasonal.png}
        \label{fig:DETha_avg}}
 	\subfloat[IT-Ro1]{\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/seasonal/ITRo1GPP_LE_WUE_seasonal.png}
        \label{fig:ITRo1_avg}}
 	\subfloat[ES-ES1]{\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/seasonal/ESES1GPP_LE_WUE_seasonal.png}
        \label{fig:ESES1_avg}}
 	\subfloat[CZ-BK1]{\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/seasonal/CZBK1GPP_LE_WUE_seasonal.png}
        \label{fig:CZBK1_avg}}
        \caption{Seasonal average (Cont.)}
\end{figure}
\begin{figure}[t]
        \centering
        \ContinuedFloat
 	\subfloat[FI-Hyy]{\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/seasonal/FIHyyGPP_LE_WUE_seasonal.png}
        \label{fig:FIHyy_avg}}
 	\subfloat[NL-Ca1]{\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_plots/seasonal/NLCa1GPP_LE_WUE_seasonal.png}
        \label{fig:NLCa1_avg}}
\caption{Seasonal average (Cont.)}
\label{fig:avg}
\end{figure}
 As already discussed, GPP is typically underestimated by both models while LE is  overestimated by JULES. Figure \ref{fig:avg} summarises this result and also highlights how close to each other the models' estimates of GPP are, while more variability arises for the latent heat fluxes, with JULES typically predicting higher values. This was already seen in the model-to-model errors shown in Tables \ref{tab:sta_mon_LE} and \ref{tab:sta_mon_GPP}. The similarity in GPP is more evident for the sites located in temperate climate. For the Mediterranean sites (\ref{fig:ITRo1_avg} and \ref{fig:ESES1_avg}) and the grass site NL-Ca1 (\ref{fig:NLCa1_avg}) the differences in carbon assimilation are larger. This is partly due to differences in the soil moisture stress parameterization and the actual soil moisture content. \\
%
In terms of WUE, it can be seen that the ecosystem WUE derived from the observed fluxes is generally higher than that of the models. Between the models, JULES has the lowest WUE, due to its higher LE flux. 
The model disagreement in latent heat fluxes can be disentangled at two levels: at the leaf level and at the ecosystem level. A the leaf level, both models present different sensitivity of stomatal pores to air humidity. Leaf level analysis in Section \ref{3-sub:gs_hum} showed how for relative humidities above 30\% stomatal conductance in JULES was larger than in CTESSEL (Figure \ref{3-fig_gs_RH}). This effect was reflected in the lower intrinsic WUE (A$_n$/g$_s$) in JULES (Figure \ref{3-fig_WUE_ca}). In those leaf level experiments, the aerodynamic conductance was fixed to the same high value in both models, ensuring good coupling between vegetation and the atmosphere and thus little or none disturbance on g$_s$. However when dealing with the ecosystem as a whole, the degree of coupling between canopy and atmosphere affects WUE \citep{deKauwe2013}. The degree of decoupling increases as the ratio of boundary layer conductance to stomatal conductance increases; the canopy becomes decoupled when boundary later conductance is low or when stomatal conductance is high \citep{Jarvis1986}. The boundary layer between the forest and the atmophere affects the calculation of g$_s$, and reduces the effect of stomatal conductance on tranpiration. In the studied models the boundary layer conductance is represented by the aerodynamic conductance, determined by   surface winspeed and the surface exchange coefficents, which are a function of roughness length and  surface layer stability. Therefore the aerodynamic conductance and consequently the degree of canopy-atmosphere coupling is a source of model discrapancy that could affect the differences in latent heat as well as determing determining the stomatal conductance. 
%Therefore the degree of coupling between canopy and atomsphere is affected by the synoptic conditions and the models parameterization of  turbulent transport at the surface.
%Although in the performed offline simulations the driving variables are the same, the structure of the model LE fluxes could be influenced not only by the leaf level stomatal conductance but also the degree of coupling assumed in both models. 
%\clearpage
%
\subsection{Diurnal validation} 
The analysis is further extended to analyse the diurnal evolution of fluxes. The 30 minute values of GPP and LE were averaged daily for the winter months (DJF: December-January-February) and summer months (JJA: June-July-August). Figures \ref{fig:BEBra_DJF_JJA}, \ref{fig:NLLoo_DJF_JJA}, \ref{fig:ITRo1_DJF_JJA} and \ref{fig:NLCa1_DJF_JJA} show the diurnal cycles at four of the modelled sites.

GPP is better reproduced in the morning and evening than in the middle of the day, corresponding to low levels of radiation, and hence photosynthesis being light limited. The relation between models' skill in reproducing GPP and the limiting factor for photosynthesis will be discussed in section \ref{sub:lim_reg}. 
The diurnal amplitude of GPP in JJA is lower than observed at all sites, in accordance to the underestimation seen at the seasonal time scale. In winter however, the diurnal amplitude modelled by JULES is higher than observed at some temperate sites, for instance Braaschat (Figure \ref{fig:BEBra_DJF_JJA}). \\
%Midday stomatal closiye

JULES presents a midday depression of CO$_2$ uptake during the summer months for many of the studied sites (the two Mediterranean sites: ES-ES1, IT-Ro1, the two continental: FI-Hyy, CZ-BK1 and one of the temperate sites: NL-Loo). The dip in GPP can be appreciated for IT-Ro1 and NL-Loo in Figures \ref{fig:ITRo1_DJF_JJA} and \ref{fig:NLLoo_DJF_JJA}. It is caused by midday stomatal closure driven by the low air humidity. However, in the majority of sites it is not seen in the the eddy covariance data nor is it reproduced by the other model. The only exception is IT-Ro1, where CTESSEL also develops a depression for both fluxes and the observations show a slight reduction (Figure \ref{fig:NLLoo_DJF_JJA}). Overall however, the feature is associated to JULES. Section \ref{3-sub:gs_hum} showed that JULES had higher sensitivity than CTESSEL to relative humidity (Figure \ref{3-fig_gs_RH}). However the strong reduction in g$_s$ was not translated into a strong reduction in A$_n$ (Figure \ref{3-fig_An_RH}). In the full model simulations, the midday depression occurs more often in GPP than in LE. In fact, the midday stomatal closure only affects the latent heat flux in the case of the Mediterranean sites, as can be seen for IT-Ro1 in Figure \ref{fig:ITRo1_DJF_JJA}, whereas at the other sites latent heat does nor reflect the stomatal closure (as seen in NL-Loo, Figure \ref{fig:NLLoo_DJF_JJA}). This seems to show that g$_s$ is not determining the evaporative flux, due to canopy being decoupled from the atmosphere or transpiration not being the main component of the total evaporation.%The reason behind LE not showing the drop at midday is most likely that at these sites transpiration, which is directly controlled by the stomatal aperture, is not the main driver of the total evapotranspiration.  
%
