\subsection{Interannual variability}
In this section the interannual variability in the observed GPP is analysed for each site. Furthermore, the interannual variability in the studied models is also analysed, in order to determine the ability of the models to reproduce the interannual variations in GPP. Two metrics are used: the annual coefficient of variation (ACV) for year to year variations in the annual mean and monthly scaled anomalies to address the interannual variability for each particular month. These statistics were calculated for all sites that had more than two years worth of data.
%
\subsubsection{Annual coefficient of variation}
The annual coefficient of variation (ACV) is computed as the ratio of the standard deviation of the mean annual GPP of all available years to the long-term mean annual.
\begin{equation}
 ACV = \frac{stdev(GPP(yr))}{\overline{GPP(yr)}}
\end{equation}
where GPP(\textit{yr}) is the mean GPP flux for year \textit{yr}. The higher ACV, the more variation is found in the annual mean form year to year. The values of ACV calculated for the eddy covariance data, JULES simulated GPP and CTESSEL simulated GPP are presented in Figure \ref{fig:ACV}. For the forest sites located in temperate climates (FR-Hes, Be-Vie, BE-Bra, NL-Loo ,DE-Tha) models tend to produce less year to year variability than observed (except CTESSEL at NL-Loo). On the other hand, at the Mediterranean sites both models exaggerate the variability, with JULES showing the highest ACV. At IT-Ro1 JULES's ACV is particularly high, due to the excessive soil moisture stress at some years.\\
%From a PFT perspective, sites with needle leaf trees showed the least year to year variability (Be-Vie, NL-Loo, DE-Tha) not very clear
It is interesting that the largest coefficient of variation is found for the grass site NL-Ca1, possibly due to the effect of dry years on short grass. Both models reproduce well the variability, coinciding in high ACV at this site. 
%
\begin{figure}
      	\centering
 	\includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_stats/ACV_GPP_tri.png}
        \caption{Annual coefficient of variation (ACV) of GPP. High coefficients indicate high interannual variation.}
        \label{fig:ACV}
\end{figure}
%
\subsubsection{Monthly scaled anomalies}
As an additional measure of interannual variability, the monthly scaled anomaly is calculated for the measurements and both models. Each month of each year is attributed an anomaly value based on the average GPP for that month over all available years. The monthly anomalies are calculated as: 
\begin{equation}
 Ano_{GPP}(m,yr) = \frac{GPP(m,yr)-\overline{GPP(m,:)}}{stdev(GPP(m,yr)-\overline{GPP(m,:)})}
\end{equation}
where $m$ represents each month and $yr$ each year. This metric informs of how a monthly mean of a particular year stands compared to the average value of that month across all years scaled by the standard deviation. The values are shown by the mesh plots in Figures \ref{fig:anom}. Each box represents one month, green colours indicate positive anomaly (GPP above the average of the considered years) and brown colors indicate negative anomaly (GPP below the average of the considered years). Note that the number of year varies for each site. The comparison is fair between models and observations for a specific site but not across sites. \\
% drought 2003
The effects of the 2003 heatwave can be attributed to the lower GPP at some sites: FR-Hes, DE-Tha and NL-Loo. In FR-Hes, the lowest GPP is found during the summer of 2004. Models reproduce this reduction, however in JULES the negative anomaly is propagated into 2007, due to a water depletion in lower layer in the subsoil. In DE-Tha 2003 heatwave effects can also be identified both in the eddy covariance data and the observations. In BE-Bra, both models do not show the high GPP anomaly seen in observations in the two fist years. Later, JULES shows negative GPP anomaly in 2006 and 2007, years which the model wrongly had soil moisture stress affecting GPP (Figure \ref{fig:FRHes_ca}).
%
In ES-ES1 and NL-Ca1 there is a progressive greening towards the last years of each data set and seems to be reproduced by the models. \\
%
\begin{figure}
      	\centering
        \subfloat[FRHes]{\includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_stats/anomaly_plots/GPP_scaled_anomaly_mesh_FRHes.png}
        \label{fig:anom_FRHes}}
        \subfloat[BEVie]{\includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_stats/anomaly_plots/GPP_scaled_anomaly_mesh_BEVie.png}
        \label{fig:anom_BEVie}}        \subfloat[BEBra]{\includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_stats/anomaly_plots/GPP_scaled_anomaly_mesh_BEBra.png}
        \label{fig:anom_BEBra}}
\caption{Scaled GPP monthly anomalies. Units are dimensionless and correspond to standard deviations.}
\end{figure}
%
\begin{figure}
        \centering
        \ContinuedFloat
        \subfloat[NLLoo]{\includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_stats/anomaly_plots/GPP_scaled_anomaly_mesh_NLLoo.png}
        \label{fig:anom_NLLoo}}
        \subfloat[DETha]{\includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{/home/gp030065/FLUXNET_stats/anomaly_plots/GPP_scaled_anomaly_mesh_DETha.png}
